    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-07-01T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-07-01T12:00:00-05:00" n="170"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d170">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A4/1222: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Acting Chairman of the American Delegation (<persName
                            corresp="#p_GHS1" type="from">Gibson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to"
                            >Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-07-01T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >July 1, 1932—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 8:11 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>294. We have had indication from different sources that the British, who said
                    they were not yet ready to discuss matters with us, have had long talks with the
                    Japanese and that they are seeking to get the Japanese lined up with them
                    against the naval portion of the President’s proposal.</p>
                <p>While <persName corresp="#p_SSJ1">Simon</persName> has put us off from day to day
                    on the ground that he was not yet ready to talk naval matters with us he has
                    today suggested a meeting of the five powers on Monday to discuss “naval
                    question”.</p>
                <p>We are bearing constantly in mind, and have so informed the British, the
                    necessity for working in good understanding in order to preserve intact our
                    general handling of Far Eastern problems. We have told them we consider it
                    essential that we iron out our difficulties in private and avoid any public
                    divergence of views.</p>
                <p>We are convinced that this is primarily <persName corresp="#p_SSJ1"
                        >Simon</persName>’s personal activity.</p>
                <p>We do not feel that this reflects any change in the point of view of the Prime
                    Minister but find difficulty in approaching him while <persName
                        corresp="#p_SSJ1">Simon</persName> is at Geneva in charge of disarmament
                    matters.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GHS1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gibson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
